  "Minamata disease demonstrated the devastating consequences of unregulated industrial discharge and the bioaccumulation of mercury in food chains. The company knew about the contamination but continued discharging for years, leading to the Minamata Convention on Mercury in 2013.": "",
  "The U.S. Clean Air Act's acid rain program reduced SO2 emissions by 67% between 1990 and 2010 at a fraction of the predicted cost. Industries had estimated compliance would cost $6 billion annually, but actual costs were about $1-2 billion. Why was the actual cost so much lower than predicted?": "",
